The opt-in frontier system-prompt variants:

  packages/opencode/src/session/prompt/gpt-frontier.txt
  packages/opencode/src/session/prompt/anthropic-frontier.txt

paraphrase selected operating principles from the Codex CLI system and review
prompts:

  Codex CLI — https://github.com/openai/codex
  Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0
  https://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0

The adapted principles are: stronger task persistence, root-cause fix preference
over surface-level patches, not fixing unrelated bugs, testing discipline
(start from the narrowest reproducer and broaden), ambition-vs-precision
judgment for existing codebases, and a preference for ripgrep. The text was
re-written for OpenCode's identity, formatting rules, and tool names; no Codex
source file is copied verbatim. The Anthropic variant ports a conservative
subset only (task-persistence language is intentionally omitted).

The following clauses in these files are original to this project and are NOT
derived from Codex:

  - the public-API silent-semantic-change elevation rule (flag a changed
    public contract — e.g. signed→unsigned comparison, nullable contract,
    ordering rule — at Medium minimum even when the type signature is
    unchanged);
  - the configured-build-tool-only rule (use the project's configured build
    tool for verification; do not fall back to raw compilers such as javac);
  - the session-end narrative-fidelity clause (when summarizing, describe only
    events citable from your own tool-call history; do not invent a mechanism
    to explain an uncertain outcome).
